<DOC><DOCNO> AP880721-0271 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-07-21-88 0236EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r f PM-OilPrices     07-21 0308</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Oil Prices,0317</SECOND><HEAD>Oil Prices Up on Hopes for Peace, OPEC Meeting</HEAD><DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Oil prices have rebounded in response to reportsthat the chances were improving for peace in the Persian Gulf andunity among OPEC producers.   The August contract for West Texas Intermediate settled up 43cents at $15.66 per barrel on Wednesday, its expiration day.   The contract had soared 84 cents on Monday and lost 47 centsTuesday as the market tried to sort out conflicting assessments ofIran's reported agreement to an immediate cease-fire in its8-year-old war with Iraq.   The market moved up strongly Wednesday in response to reportsthat the United Nations would send a negotiating team to Iran andIraq to nail down the details of the cease-fire.   Traders said the latest news appeared to bolster chances forpeace in the war-torn region, which in turn could lead to bettercooperation among oil producers, who have been flooding worldmarkets with oil to fund the war effort.   Also Wednesday, rumors circulated in the market that the pricemonitoring committee of the Organziation of Petroleum ExportingCountries would meet early next month to discuss way to rein inproduction and stabilize oil prices.   Heating oil made an even stronger upward move than crude oil.Bob Baker of Prudential-Bache Securities Inc. said the latestinventory reports showed supplies were not increasing as much asexpected. He said the recent heat wave may have put a drain onsupplies as utilities turned to oil to meet peak power demands andshippers resorted to moving goods by truck as an alternative toriver barges.   The contract for August delivery of No.2 heating oil gained 1.75cents to 44.65 cents a gallon on the New York Merc. The contractfor August delivery of unleaded gasoline rose .20 cent to 50.85cents a gallon.</TEXT></DOC>